has a Student&#x27;s &quot;t&quot; distribution with formula_41 degrees of freedom. Note that the distribution of formula_42 does not depend on the values of the unobservable parameters formula_34 and formula_44; i.e., it is a pivotal quantity. Suppose we wanted to calculate a 95% confidence interval for formula_45 Then, denoting formula_46 as the 97.5th percentile of this distribution,

: formula_47

Note that &quot;97.5th&quot; and &quot;0.95&quot; are correct in the preceding expressions. There is a 2.5% chance that formula_42 will be less than formula_49 and a 2.5% chance that it will be larger than formula_50 Thus, the probability that formula_42 will be between formula_49 and formula_53 is 95%. formula_54 is the probability measure under the student formula_55 distribution.

